/r9k/ is an imageboard where there are no exact reposts.

1. If you attempt to post something unoriginal, it is not posted, and you are muted temporarily.
2. The time with which you are muted for doubles with each transgression.
3. Each mute time is 2^n in seconds where n is the number of times you have transgressed. So, your mute time doubles each time you fuck up.
4. Backlinks, eg >>1, are not viewed by the robot. So "lolwut" and ">>2 lolwut" are the same post, in the eyes of the robot.
5. Gibberish at the end of a post to force originality may result in mod intervention (no BLOX posts please).
6. Images are NOT included in the filter, only text.
7. Your mute count slowly decreases over time.
8. You cannot post a picture without text.
9. Unicode is blocked. Sorry, too many exploits (Cyrillic letters, etc).
10. Posts require a certain minimum amount of original content in order to be posted.
11. Post sane, real content, well thought out replies, and mutes are unlikely.
12. The original algorithm was designed by XKCD:
http://blag.xkcd.com/2008/01/14/robot9000-and-xkcd-signal-attacking-noise-in-chat/

posts.com:
The Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) is an Internet standard communication protocol for electronic mail transmission. Mail servers and other message transfer agents use SMTP to send and receive mail messages. User-level email clients typically use SMTP only for sending messages to a mail server for relaying, and typically submit outgoing email to the mail server on port 587 or 465 per RFC 8314. For retrieving messages, IMAP (which replaced the older POP3) is standard, but proprietary servers also often implement proprietary protocols, e.g., Exchange ActiveSync.

SMTP's origins began in 1980, building on concepts implemented on the ARPANET since 1971. It has been updated, modified and extended multiple times. The protocol version in common use today has extensible structure with various extensions for authentication, encryption, binary data transfer, and internationalized email addresses. SMTP servers commonly use the Transmission Control Protocol on port number 25 (for plaintext) and 587 (for encrypted communications).

I think it's probably more reliable than the online tests, but only if you don't have confirmation bias. If you have any confirmation bias it's way worse, because you'll structure your words in a manner that the AI gives you the answer you're seeking. You also have to avoid buzzwords that are associated with types. Because the AI will automatically associate you with that type.

Where AI excels is getting detailed, easy to understand information about functions, types, and function slots (inferior as example) so that you can make an accurate assessment of your type with the information.
You've basically got the best translator in the world, that can condense large portions of text into something easy to read and understand. Use it to actually understand what Jung was actually saying, not to selfishly confirm that you're some super unique speshul type.
Expand your knowledge.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Lately, I've been reflecting on my cousin's life and observing the outpour of support and love from many of his family and friends. My cousin lived a very unconventional life. I think to a common outsider, they would see his life and think he wasted it away because he didn't experience many "rites-of-passages."

He never had a girlfriend, experienced intimacy, lived on his own, drove, never went to college/university. He travelled very minimally, and only started to work only a few years before he died. He was very much a homebody -- wouldn't leave the house weeks at a time -- and he never "grew up." He still held his childhood passions -- mostly 80s/90s pop culture (retro video games, music, movies, toys, cartoons, fashion). While people his age were talking about marriage, career, starting their own family, etc. etc. he almost exclusively talked about 80s/90s culture, and made constant pop culture references.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com: I refuse to elaborate on the shire garn offload it

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
He was the sweetest, most innocent, pure, kindest person I have ever known. He rarely ever got angry or negative, and there didn't seem to be a "bad bone" in his body -- not even when he was confronted with his eventual death. Perhaps an outside observer would see him and think him weak and weird, because he didn't fit the mold of an "alpha" male.

But, despite all this, his life mattered so much to so many people. He left an imprint on so many people's lives, whether they were long-term friends, or mere acquiantances. He mattered so much to friends and family, despite not being "conventionally successful."

I've always felt I had to justify my value and existence to others by meeting the standards others/society set that determines "success." And, I still do. But, it is very beautiful seeing the amount of love and impact his life had on so many people, and truly how many people will miss him. His manager and co-workers even made a statement saying how they felt my cousin was like a "family member" to them.

He seemed content about not having the things that most people strove for. I think he never wanted those things -- however, I think near the end of his life, he wanted to experience a relationship and intimacy. Before he got sick. He joined some online dating sites, but to no avail. I don't know what his thoughts were about that in his final few weeks, but regardless, I don't think it matters anymore.

I don't really know why I am writing this. Make of it what you will. As I said, I am so used to being judged for my value/social status, and being "lesser" if I don't possess certain things. Yet, my cousin never had any of these things people strive for, and he left such an immeasurable impact on people's lives and memories.

posts.sub: How Online Services Work (and How to exploit them for profit)
posts.com:
There's thousands of online services that are desperately trying to gain customers in an increasingly competitive attention economy.

What I'm about to reveal to you applies to services that meet the following conditions:
>It's a primarily online business with no tangible product.
>All the overhead could potentially be offset by a single person's labour (not counting utilities).
>They use click funnels (basically, pages lead to pages lead to a 'special offer' with an expiration, usually 8 - 50 hours)
These are typically online learning platforms, so typically that I'm struggling to think of another example - maybe some niche media companies or streaming services?

If you're a dumb ass you'll pay for many of these, if you're a midwit you'll maybe buy one or two and then stop signing up for them because you either got what you wanted, or realised you're too lazy to take advantage of these online services, if you're smart you'll never give your email to these vipers, if you're a goddamn genius here's what you do:
>Set up a burner email
>Sign up for every one of these services (unless they require cc details)
>Wait

You know what happens?

Pic related happens. You might think I still have to pay *something*, but, in fact, this would defeat the purpose for them (yes, really). If I've held out for this long then best practice says they should give me something for free that will come at negligible expense to themselves, I checked it out and the average cost of one of their courses was $125, going as low as $45. They've just given me 10 courses as a matter of best business practices. Think about it:
>The service already exists
>Every businessman already knows good will creates customers
>There's no reason for them to not, eventually, give it to you for free.

18 months is the average amount of time it takes for them to give you a voucher to spend on their website.

Part two will be how you can profit from this.
